{{Infobox stadium | name = Alexandra Recreation Ground | nickname = Nantwich Road | image = | caption = | fullname = | location = [[Crewe]], [[England]] | coordinates = {{Coord|53.0884|-2.4356|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 1877 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = 1896 | demolished = | owner = | surface = Grass | cost = | architect = | capacity = | record_attendance = 7,000 | dimensions = | acreage = | volume = | tenants = [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] }}
The '''Alexandra Recreation Ground''', also known as '''Nantwich Road''', was a multi-sport venue in [[Crewe]] in [[England]]. It was the home ground of [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]], and also hosted an [[England national football team|England]] home match and an [[FA Cup]] semi-final.
==History== The ground was opened in 1877, and was used for athletics, cricket, cycle racing and football. An oval ground, it had a stand around 100 feet long on the western side and banking around the remainder of the pitch.<ref name=UD>Paul Smith & Shirley Smith (2005) ''The Ultimate Directory of English & Scottish Football League Grounds Second Edition 1888–2005'', Yore Publications, p13, {{ISBN|0954783042}}</ref>
In the [[1886–87 FA Cup|1886–87 season]] the ground was the venue of the [[FA Cup]] semi-final between [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], with the attendance of 7,000 probably being the ground record. On 4 February 1888 the ground [[England national football team home stadium|hosted]] the opening match of the [[1887–88 British Home Championship]], which saw [[England national football team|England]] beat [[Wales national football team|Wales]] 5–1. Crewe were founder members of the [[Football League Second Division]] in 1892, and the first League match played at the ground saw Crewe defeat [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] 1–0 in front of 2,000 spectators.<ref name=UD/>
The last match at the ground was played on 28 March 1896, with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool's]] 7–0 win on the day also being Crewe's record home defeat at the ground. However, it was not Crewe's last home league match of the season, which was played at the Vicarage in the nearby town of [[Sandbach]]. Crewe were voted out of the Football League at the end of the [[1895–96 Football League|1895–96 season]], and subsequently played at several different grounds until returning to the area to play at the original Gresty Road ground in 1897.<ref name=UD/> They later moved to the modern-day [[Gresty Road]] ground in 1906.<ref>Smith & Smith, p62</ref>
The Alexandra Recreation Ground is now the site of the Rail House office building, a car park and part of the modern Gresty Road stadium.<ref name=UD/>
