{{Use British English| date=July 2016}} {{Use dmy dates| date=July 2016}}
{{Infobox organization | name = Qhubeka | logo = File:Qhubeka Foundation logo.jpg | logo_size = 200px | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | abbreviation = | motto = <nowiki>#bicycleschangelives</nowiki> | formation = 2005 | founder = Anthony Fitzhenry | location = South Africa | coords = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|display=inline, title}} --> | website = {{URL|qhubeka.org/2013/}} }}
'''Qhubeka''' is a [[South Africa]]n not-for-profit organisation that donates bicycles as part of the [[World Bicycle Relief]]'s charity programme in South Africa. Qhubeka is currently supported by the [[Dimension Data (cycling team)|Dimension Data]] [[UCI World Tour]] cycling team (formerly MTN-Qhubeka).
==History== The Qhubeka was founded in 2005 by Anthony Fitzhenry. The name Qhubeka means "to move forward" in [[Nguni languages|Nguni]], and as of 2014 the charity had delivered over 45,000 bicycles.<ref name="UCI">{{cite news| url= http://www.uci.ch/cyclingforall/qhubeka-mobilising-population/| title= Qhubeka: mobilising a population| publisher=[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]| date=22 August 2014| access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref><ref name="WS">{{cite news|url= http://www.wheelsuckers.co.uk/profiles/blogs/the-team-putting-a-smile-back-on-the-face-of-pro-cycling| title= MTN-Qhubeka: Cycling to end the cycle of poverty| last=Nash| first=John| work=Wheel Suckers| date=21 March 2013| accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref><ref name="MU">{{cite news|url= http://www.mediaupdate.co.za/publicity/55239/samsung-electronics-sa-donates-r2-million-to-the-qhubeka-initiative| title= Samsung Electronics SA donates R2-million to the Qhubeka initiative| work=Media Update| date=24 July 2013| access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref> Qhubeka provides bicycles for children to attend schools, and for adults to attend work, with estimates suggesting a 75% reduction in commuting time and 23% higher attendance at schools for people given a bicycle by the Qhubeka.<ref name="UCI"/><ref name="Velo">{{cite news|url= http://www.velonation.com/News/ID/15824/Giro-dItalia-organiser-RCS-Sport-and-Qhubeka-hand-out-bikes-in-South-African-charity-initiative.aspx| title= Giro d’Italia organiser RCS Sport and Qhubeka hand out bikes in South African charity initiative|work=Velo Nation| date=15 November 2013| access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref> In order to be given a bicycle, the recipients are first required to take bicycle safety and maintenance training courses.<ref name="You">{{cite news|url= http://www.you.co.za/news/this-great-initiative-is-changing-lives-one-bicycle-at-a-time/| title= This great initiative is changing lives one bicycle at a time| last=Luiz| first=Samantha| work=You.co.za| date=30 January 2016| access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref> The organisation also donates one bicycle for every 100 trees grown, or for every ton of rubbish collected.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.southafrica.info/about/social/teammtnqhubeka-020513.htm#.V46bkrgrLIU| title= Qhubeka: bicycles for rural development| work=SouthAfrica.info| date=2 May 2013| accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref>
In 2013, the organisation became part of the [[World Bicycle Relief]],<ref name="UCI"/> and in November 2013, [[RCS Sport]], the organisers of the [[Giro d'Italia]], donated 58 bicycles to Qhubeka.<ref name="Velo"/> In 2014, Qhubeka encouraged people to ride for 67 minutes and donate R67 on [[Mandela Day]],<ref>{{cite news|url= http://fullsus.co.za/mandela-day-marathon-mtb-dash-partners-with-qhubeka/| title= MANDELA DAY MARATHON MTB DASH PARTNERS WITH QHUBEKA| work=Full SUS| date=2014| accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref> and the Berg and Bush mountain bike race in [[KwaZulu-Natal]] chose Qhubeka as their charity to support.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.fullstopcom.com/media-room-mainmenu-18/features/1774-berg-and-bush-adopts-qhubeka-initiative.html| title=Berg and Bush adopts Qhubeka initiative| work=Full Stop Communications| date=26 June 2015| accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref> In 2015, the organisation donated 5,020 bicycles,<ref name="You"/> and in June 2016 100 bicycles were donated by [[AutoTrader.co.za|Auto Trader]].<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.bizcommunity.com/Article/196/627/147154.html| title= 360 bicycles donated to Qhubeka in AutoTrader #DriveChange campaign| work=Biz Community| date=30 June 2016| accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref>
==Professional cycling== In 2011, [[MTN Group]] changed the name of their UCI Continental Team from Team MTN to [[MTN-Qhubeka]], in order to promote the organisation.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://themediaonline.co.za/2012/02/briefly-mtn-cycle-team-gets-new-look/| title= Briefly…MTN cycle team gets new look| work=The Media Online| date=27 February 2012| accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref> In 2013, [[Samsung]], who sponsored the MTN-Qhubeka team, donated R2 million to the charity.<ref name="MU"/> For the 2016 season, the [[UCI World Tour]] team was renamed Dimension Data for Qhubeka, to clarify that the team were supporting the Qhubeka charity, rather than receiving sponsorship from them.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/dimension_data_new_title_sponsor_for_mtn_qhubeka| title= Dimension Data new title sponsor for MTN-Qhubeka| last=Nelson| first=Adam| work=[[SportsPro]]| date=28 September 2015| accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref> During the [[2016 Tour de France]], the Dimension Data team also took part in the Qhubeka 5000 fundraising initiative, which aims to deliver 5,000 bicycles in 2016. The initiative encouraged people to ride between {{convert|6|km|mi}} to {{convert|208|km|mi}};<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.supersport.com/cycling/sa-cycling/news/160627/Three_Africans_in_DiData_TdF_team| title= Three Africans in DiData TdF team| work=[[SuperSport (South African TV channel)|SuperSport]]| date=27 June 2016| access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://highfive.co.uk/news/qhubeka5000| title= Ride to fund bicycles to mobilise people in South Africa| work=High5| date=1 July 2016| access-date=19 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.bikebiz.com/news/read/met-for-qhubeka/019751| title= MET for Qhubeka| last=Howells| first=Kieran| work=Bike Biz| date=30 June 2016| accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> during the first two weeks of the Tour, the Qhubeka charity received R600,000.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.sabc.co.za/news/a/f60781804d8162f994c9de4b5facb1b5/More-than-half-a-million-raised-for-charity-by-Qhubeka-20161507| title=More than half a million raised for charity by Qhubeka| last=Olivier| first=Harry| work=[[South African Broadcasting Corporation]]| date=15 July 2016| accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref>
