{{ infobox national water polo team | Name = Soviet Union | Nickname = | Association = Федерация водного поло СССР | Confederation = [[Ligue Européenne de Natation|LEN]] (Europe) | Image = Flag of the Soviet Union.svg | Most caps = | Top scorer = | Home Stadium = | FINA Trigramme = URS
| First game = | Largest win = | Largest loss = | Olympics apps = 9 | Olympics first = 1952 | Olympics best = {{gold01}} ([[Water polo at the 1972 Summer Olympics|1972]], [[Water polo at the 1980 Summer Olympics|1980]]) | World champ apps = 6 | World champ first = 1973 | World champ best = {{gold01}} ([[Water polo at the 1975 World Aquatics Championships – Men's tournament|1975]], [[Water polo at the 1982 World Aquatics Championships – Men's tournament|1982]]) | World cup apps = 6 | World cup first = 1979 | World cup best = {{gold01}} ([[1981 FINA Men's Water Polo World Cup|1981]], [[1983 FINA Men's Water Polo World Cup|1983]]) | Regional name = | Regional cup apps = | Regional cup first = | Regional cup best = }}
The '''Soviet Union men's national water polo team''' represented the [[Soviet Union]] in international [[water polo]] competitions. After the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]], the [[Russia men's national water polo team|Russian national water polo team]] became the successor of Soviet team.
